{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411374"},"attributes":{"position":1,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478803"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"18812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18812"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.03,0.14,0.79]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79420"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11545"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64742"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2663"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79420"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with three days of lethargy, poor feeding, and rapid breathing. His parent reports he had a fever and runny nose last week that seemed to improve, but he has become increasingly tired. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic. His pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 85/45 mmHg, respiratory rate 45/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has cool peripheries and delayed capillary refill. Heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. There are bilateral fine crackles at the lung bases. His liver edge is palpable 3 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETroponin T: 250 ng/L (\u0026lt;14)\u003Cbr /\u003EBrain natriuretic peptide: 1500 pg/mL (\u0026lt;100)\u003Cbr /\u003EChest X-ray shows cardiomegaly with pulmonary congestion\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchiolitis","Diabetic ketoacidosis","Pneumonia","Septic shock","Myocarditis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features suggestive of heart failure following a viral prodrome. The combination of lethargy, tachycardia, respiratory distress, and signs of poor perfusion, along with markedly elevated cardiac biomarkers, is highly suggestive of acute \u003Cstrong\u003Emyocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E. The recent viral illness is a common precipitant, and the progression from mild viral symptoms to cardiovascular compromise is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiolitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with cough, wheeze, and respiratory distress but would not explain the significantly elevated cardiac biomarkers or signs of poor perfusion. Additionally, bronchiolitis is more common in infants under 12 months of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly with poor perfusion and tachycardia. However, the preceding viral illness that improved, followed by deterioration, along with the marked elevation in cardiac biomarkers, makes myocarditis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause lethargy and tachycardia but would typically present with polyuria, polydipsia, and metabolic acidosis. The elevated cardiac biomarkers and cardiomegaly on chest X-ray would not be explained by DKA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the respiratory symptoms and crackles but would not account for the cardiomegaly, hepatomegaly, or significantly elevated cardiac biomarkers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMyocarditis in children can be challenging to diagnose due to its non-specific presentation. The combination of a recent viral illness, signs of heart failure (tachycardia, respiratory distress, hepatomegaly), and elevated cardiac biomarkers (troponin and BNP) strongly supports the diagnosis. These children require prompt recognition and management as they can rapidly deteriorate into cardiogenic shock.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Myocarditis in children commonly presents with non-specific symptoms including fatigue, poor feeding, and respiratory distress.","Elevated troponin and brain natriuretic peptide levels are key diagnostic markers in pediatric myocarditis.","Early recognition and supportive management of myocarditis is crucial as children can rapidly deteriorate into cardiogenic shock."],"references":["Williams JL, Jacobs HM, Lee S. Pediatric Myocarditis. Cardiol Ther. 2023 Jun;12(2):243-260. doi: 10.1007/s40119-023-00309-6. Epub 2023 Mar 11. PMID: 36906691; PMCID: PMC10008072."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64742"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64742"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T12:28:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T12:29:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11545"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79420"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":